are others who are bitten by the bug but they just do not recognize it as yet .I love cars, most of all, I love performance cars . That said, there will be no car discrimination round here. It does not make a difference which year , make, or model car you own , if it is worthy to be classified a yaAd machine it will be on these pages. It is my duty, my responsibility, to use this medium to provide material which will show what the creative Jamaican mind has conceived. Information relating to the automobile industry in Jamaica will also be available with just one click of the rat (mouse). From one Yaad man to all - Machine Deh Ya!','',-2,0,0,0,'2004-08-19 20:11:07',62,'','2006-07-07 22:45:20',62,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2004-08-19 00:00:00','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','','menu_image=-1\nitem_title=1\npageclass_sfx=\nback_button=0\nrating=0\nauthor=0\ncreatedate=0\nmodifydate=0\npdf=0\nprint=0\nemail=0',1,0,0,'','',0,0),(6,'Labour Day Project- Dover. 23/05/06','News1','<p><em><strong>Proverb &ndash; Some men are wise and some are otherwise.</strong> </em><br /></p><p>A public holiday usually poses a very peculiar problem where I am concerned. I usually want to cool out, take a break from the hustle and bustle of the weekly grind(Monday to Friday work week) and just soak in some of the tropical paradise which whether we believe it or not we have here. This plan is usually ripped to shreds when upon arriving at the spot it is as crowded as a lotto shop at 6;55pm when the pot has soared past the 20 million dollar mark. As such to maintain sanity I usually remain home,bored stiff but sane and safe.</p>','<br /><br />This time around I was of the view that there was light at the end of what appeared to be a never ending tunnel of darkness. The life line came in the form of the Jamaica Race Drivers Club initiative to launch its first annual Labour Day Work Project at Dover. Honesty is the best policy. I will be the first to tell you that there is no better meaning to be provided for the word lazy, that a passport size picture of my frowning face next to the term in the dictionary could not defeat effortlessly. There was a section of the information released which demanded my attention. This line was the culprit &ndash; &lsquo;later in the day an informal driving/lapping school will be available courtesy of some of the veteran drivers who will be on hand&rsquo;. I searched high, low and in between and I saw neither cost nor entry fee. This was a show up, clean up Dover and be taught how to drive at Dover .The atom bomb that devastated Hiroshima did not produce the blast I carried in my head after I read that. There are times when you are told that if something sounds too good to be true it probably is. I was willing to find out.<br /><br />At Dover the sun did not realize it was a public holiday and as such it should be at rest. Hell no &ndash; get it &ndash; the sun was out in all its glory. The JAGAS group and others were busy at various sections of the circuit toiling in the brilliant tropical sunshine. The labour day project was on in earnest. It is very easy to recognize when persons out of their field expertise. Take painting for example, if you see more paint on the person than on the wall, you know he or she is out of his element. Team Mobay representatives were busy painting themselves (Kirk) and a little bit of the building. Teddy Burton was much more successful at story telling than he was at assisting the workmen in his pit area.<br /><br /> Some members of team RS spent more time labouring on Thomas&rsquo;s ride the than they did on anything else. Thomas had a hilarious drama relating to taking a corner at speed and feeling the seat turning with him! His seat did require immediate attention, so in my book they had a valid excuse. Ice at various stages appeared to be working, as to how successful he was or what he accomplished I will allow him to explain. Dean/Duct Tape was always focused on the task at hand and thought it was his responsibility to break up any little lime that would begin to distract the workers. At one a stage there was a raging debate about the popularity of Nascar and football and Dean had to intervene with the &lsquo;back to work order&rsquo;. Real slave driver. . Hollywood tried his hand at painting but did not realize that we do not use a roller to paint grills but paint he did.<br /><br />The con artists for the day must be David Summerbell Jr and Peter Rae. David carried his children, who adore their accomplished father. His daughter was busy defending his honor when we informed her that if he ever made the mistake of entering the IP 45 class next race meet he could call it quits as a result of the sound beating he would receive at the hands of the aspiring Schumachers. Without flinching her two questions were- &lsquo;1) my daddy and 2) what will he be driving. When our response was not to her liking she responded by saying &lsquo;you are scared&rsquo;. Their admiration was evident. It was pretty obvious that David is the man to check for pointers as to how to successfully brainwash your child. As I said con artist number one, David, was busier with his kids than with any thing else, providing parental care. Peter Rae on the other hand had his workman present so guess who did all the work &ndash; Peter, God forbid &ndash;he might hurt a nail. Based on what I saw the Jagas fellows did a lot of work and should be commended for their effort. Most of the persons who were at the venue, pitched in and played a role, despite how minute it might have been. Picture this, Monique in a one of those jeans pants that women have to jump in to get them to fit. So the picture is Monique in that pair of jeans, a T-shirt a few sizes too small (referred to as tight blouse) and now add to the outfit a broom. Yes she was very busy sweeping from corner to corner in the pits. <br /><br />Food was available and after a little price arrangement (half cost) it was lunch time. At the end of that much needed break Doug went around to the various pits and announced that it was time for the convoy. The convoy would see persons going around the track in their cars following one of the veterans. Yes, it was really happening this was no dream, no politicians promise, no promise is comfort to a fool. A second or third announcement was not necessary &ndash; all drivers and non drivers were ready to go. Who would not want to run laps around the circuit.<br /><br /> Before we got the opportunity to experience the track an informal drivers meeting was held on track. At this stage it was explained in no uncertain terms that this was definitely not a race. The purpose of the exercise was twofold. Individuals will be taught the lines of the circuit and also individuals will be allowed to have fun under supervision. The veterans to lead each group were Doug, Dean and Teddy. We formed our lines, 5 cars behind each veteran (Teddy was given veteran status for the day) and off we went . <br /><br />I took the liberty of planting myself in Kirk&rsquo;s Evo 6 to get a view and experience the track from the passenger seat. As was explained by the veterans Dover was very hard on the car. David spent a lot of time explaining that during a break in the runs. In about 3-4 laps the cars were brought in to cool down. If you are a fan of scents race related &ndash;disc pads, fuel etc., you would have had your fill. I remember a Team RS member remarking &lsquo;smell the fumes&rsquo;.<br /><br /> The convoy was for familiarization but that could not prepare me for the next segment. The second segment saw the veterans driving the various cars with the owners and others who were brave enough to sit in them during the assault. As stated I was rooted in the Evo 6 and as such when Doug decided to drive the Evo 6 I became back seat passenger. Doug is someone who I would have known as a regular at every thing Jamaican motor sports. I have seen him in action and I have been fortunate to witness some of his exploits when he changes gear and becomes &lsquo;Hollywood&rsquo;. I will give an example the last sprint in Ironshore he did a 360 with the evo and on the second revolution he stopped midway slipped the car in reverse and drove into the pits perfect parking. Mobay was senseless money, liquor and women were being thrown in the air in celebration of a dramatic stunt by their local actor. I say all that to say this, I was comfortable all the way. I have read everything there is to read about the Evo but I have never been in one with a professional race car driver. During our assault on the circuit not only were we traveling at hair raising speeds, testing the traction, cornering and braking abilities of the Evo 6, Doug was also explaining as we drove what to do, what not to do, how to negotiate particular corners, which gear is best for the various corners and how to be smooth with gentle steering input etc. I obviously will not disclose some of the secrets he gave away he still has races ahead. I was shown how an Evo should be driven and I thoroughly enjoyed it. I did not get a chance to drive with Dean in the dew machine but I did get a chance to run a few laps with Ice in his machine. The runs I had in Ice&rsquo;s car and the runs I saw being made by Dean&rsquo;s car and based on the comments being made by all the persons who either drove or drove in the Type R I will not hesitate to give the cars the respect they deserve. They are excellent cars and that was made abundantly clear on the track. All the persons who showed up were allowed to participate and participate they did.<br /><br /><br />In the final analysis we all had fun, we were allowed to run until the sun decided to leave us Doug ran the wind out of 2 evos when he was through an egg could be fried on the rotors of the cars. I must say thanks to the veterans, it was appreciated and I hope that similar type events will be planned to get more persons involved at the competing level. Yes, Dean the Honda Type R is truly a remarkable car. What I found most interesting was the fact that the 71 horsepower Toyota Vitz that Teddy drove was such a competent performer on track. At one stage Ice was keeping close tabs on the BZR during one of the runs. Thomas spent some time very very close to the wall, he had his partner uncomfortable at time to time. We told her he was ok that was the correct line . This is not the tell all piece, you should have been there . Again thanks veterans lesson for the day delivered &ndash; skill is stronger than strength.<br /><br /><br /><br />Machine Deh Ya!',1,1,0,1,'2004-07-07 11:54:06',62,'','2006-07-29 15:25:01',62,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2004-07-07 00:00:00','0000-00-00 00:00:00','car2.jpg|left||0||bottom||','','pageclass_sfx=\nback_button=\nitem_title=1\nlink_titles=\nintrotext=1\nsection=0\nsection_link=0\ncategory=0\ncategory_link=0\nrating=\nauthor=\ncreatedate=\nmodifydate=\npdf=\nprint=\nemail=\nkeyref=\ndocbook_type=',12,0,18,'','',0,40),(7,'Example News Item 2','News2','<p>{mosimage}Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consetetur sadipscing elitr, sed diam nonumy eirmod tempor invidunt ut labore et dolore magna aliquyam erat,\r\nsed diam voluptua. At vero eos et accusam et justo duo dolores et ea rebum. Stet clita kasd gubergren, no sea takimata sanctus est Lorem ipsum dolor sit\r\namet. Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consetetur sadipscing elitr, sed diam nonumy eirmod tempor invidunt ut labore et dolore magna aliquyam erat, sed diam\r\nvoluptua. At vero eos et accusam et justo duo dolores et ea rebum. Stet clita kasd gubergren, no sea takimata sanctus est Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet. Lorem\r\nipsum dolor sit amet, consetetur sadipscing elitr, sed diam nonumy eirmod tempor invidunt ut labore et dolore magna aliquyam erat, sed diam voluptua. At\r\nvero eos et accusam et justo duo dolores et ea rebum. Stet clita kasd gubergren, no sea takimata sanctus est Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet.</p>','',-2,1,0,1,'2004-07-07 11:54:06',62,''